To achieve continuous improvement of emergency response processes, records should be retained post-incident to enable review of actions taken during the incident response. Such records may include but are not limited to:

1. An incident response template filled in with information from the coordination meeting;

2. Incident artifacts, including files, screenshots, documents, and links;

3. Chat transcripts from the approved communication channels specified in A.1.8.1.3 - Emergency Response Communication Channels.

It is at the discretion of the Support Facilitators as to whether incident records can be shared with entities outside of the Emergency Response Group.

The [code]plans[/code] parameter is an array of scheduled Spells to be canceled. Each scheduled Spell to be canceled is represented as a [code]Plan[/code] struct:

[code]/**
 * @notice A struct representing a plan.
 * @param usr The address of the scheduled spell.
 * @param tag The tag identifying the address.
 * @param fax The encoded call to be made in `usr`.
 * @param eta The expiration time.
 */
struct Plan {
    address usr;
    bytes32 tag;
    bytes fax;
    uint256 eta;
}[/code]

The parameters of the [code]Plan[/code] struct are defined in A.1.9.4.3.1.3 - Protego Parameters.

By way of example only and without limiting the generality of the principle described in A.2.10.1.1.1.4.4 - Refund Of Amounts To Resilience Fund, such amounts include, without limitation:

• Amounts awarded by a court towards the Beneficiary’s legal fees or disbursements;

• An award of damages to a Beneficiary in relation to a Claim Event;

• Monies or digital assets located by police or other investigative bodies that were identified as the property of Sky; and

• Interest payable to a Beneficiary in relation to a Claim Event.

The Core Executor Agents should consider the level of Actively Stabilizing Collateral (see A.3.4.2.2.1 - Actively Stabilizing Collateral) using the following non-binding guidelines:

• If total ASC is above 30%, consider decreasing the Base Rate by approximately 2%;
• If total ASC is between 28% and 30%, consider decreasing the Base Rate by approximately 1%;
• If total ASC is between 26% and 28%, consider decreasing the Base Rate by approximately 0.3%;
• If total ASC is between 24% and 26%, consider maintaining the Base Rate at approximately its current level;
• If total ASC is between 22% and 24%, consider increasing the Base Rate by approximately 0.3%;
• If total ASC is between 20% and 22%, consider increasing the Base Rate by approximately 1%; and
• If total ASC is below 20%, consider increasing the Base Rate by approximately 2%.
